"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Caithness, Scotland":"Caithness, Schotland"},"en":{"Abt 1076–1154":"about 1076–1154","1085–1152":"1085–1152","1098–1142":"1098–1142","1128–Male":"1128–Deceased","1140–1198":"1140–1198","1076–1154":"1076–1154","1154":"1154","1198":"1198","1098":"1098","1142":"1142","1076":"1076","1152":"1152","1140":"1140","1085":"1085","Abt 1076":"about 1076","1129":"1129","1128":"1128","about 1128":"about 1128","before 1152":"before 1152","Orkney, Scotland":"Orkney, Scotland, United Kingdom","Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland":"Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Caithness, Scotland":"Caithness, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Countess","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire, of Norman origin): from Middle English <i>contas(e)</i>, Old French <i>contesse</i> ‘countess’, applied as a nickname for a proud, haughty woman or for a foppish man, or as an occupational name for a servant of a countess."],"variants":[{"name":"Countiss","meanings":["English: variant of   Countess  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Haakonsdater Countess Countess was born about 1076, in Orkney, Scotland, United Kingdom. She married Madach first Earl of Athol in 1129, in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1154, in her hometown, at the age of 79."},"et":{"Abt 1076–1154":"umbes 1076–1154","1085–1152":"1085–1152","1098–1142":"1098–1142","1128–Mal